And then I will be sharing the slides with you all directly afterwards,

00:03:16.000 --> 00:03:22.000
so no need to kind of have your notepad and pencil ready. You can just sit back, relax, and take it all in.

00:03:22.000 --> 00:03:28.000
I also will say that there will be a few moments during today's session that if you want to follow along

00:03:28.000 --> 00:03:31.000
and actually write some R code, it'll be very minimal R code.

00:03:31.000 --> 00:03:38.000
But if you do have RStudio open, either your local desktop application or maybe using Posit Cloud or Posit Workbench,

00:03:38.000 --> 00:03:42.000
wherever you access RStudio, just feel free to have that open,

00:03:42.000 --> 00:03:49.000
and then I'll kind of direct you to that RStudio session a little bit as we go through today's session.

00:03:49.000 --> 00:03:51.000
So what are we going to talk about today?

00:03:51.000 --> 00:03:56.000
Well, this is going to be all about package management in R, so obviously we're going to be talking about packages.

00:03:56.000 --> 00:03:59.000
But we're also going to be focusing on libraries and repositories.

00:03:59.000 --> 00:04:03.000
These are going to be the big three topics for today's session.

00:04:03.000 --> 00:04:07.000
We're going to talk about what happens when things go wrong in your package management strategy,

00:04:07.000 --> 00:04:15.000
and also some strategies and tools to either prevent things from going wrong or to kind of fix them if they happen to.

00:04:15.000 --> 00:04:19.000
Here's some other resources that I collected when creating this presentation.

00:04:19.000 --> 00:04:26.000
So, again, I'll forward these slides over, some great presentations, some documentation to read through.

00:04:26.000 --> 00:04:30.000
And then one more thing to keep in mind before we dive into today's topic,

00:04:30.000 --> 00:04:36.000
if you were hoping I was going to stand up here and say, this is how you manage your packages in R,

00:04:36.000 --> 00:04:38.000
that would be great if I could do that.

00:04:38.000 --> 00:04:43.000
But unfortunately, there is no single solution for managing packages in R.

00:04:43.000 --> 00:04:45.000
And why is that?

00:04:45.000 --> 00:04:47.000
That's because every team is a little bit different.

00:04:47.000 --> 00:04:52.000
So here I have listed just a few variables that can differ from one team to the next,

00:04:52.000 --> 00:04:58.000
such as are you running R and RStudio locally on your desktop, or are you running on a server?

00:04:58.000 --> 00:05:01.000
Are you in an air-gapped or offline environment?

00:05:01.000 --> 00:05:07.000
Do you work in what's known as a validated environment, very popular with our pharmaceutical customers?

00:05:07.000 --> 00:05:10.000
How secure is your IT or security team?

00:05:10.000 --> 00:05:12.000
Who manages the environment?

00:05:12.000 --> 00:05:14.000
Is it the users or the admin?

00:05:14.000 --> 00:05:22.000
And can a data scientist update a package to the latest and greatest, or are they kind of locked down to a specific version?

00:05:22.000 --> 00:05:27.000
So because all of these things differ from one team to the next, again, we're not going to have a single solution for you all.

00:05:27.000 --> 00:05:40.000
But my goal is to provide you with a lot of topics and things to consider so that you can develop your own internal package management strategy specific for your group.

00:05:40.000 --> 00:05:46.000
So to kick things off, I'm going to show on the screen here an error message that no matter who you are,

00:05:46.000 --> 00:05:52.000
if you've written any bit of R code, I guarantee you at some point you've hit this error message.

00:05:52.000 --> 00:05:53.000
So what are we doing here?

00:05:53.000 --> 00:06:01.000
So we're trying to load the ggplot2 package, which is popular for data visualization, using the library function in R.

00:06:01.000 --> 00:06:06.000
And we get this scary red text saying there is no package called ggplot2.

00:06:06.000 --> 00:06:11.000
Now, if you've been using R for a couple of years now, you may know exactly what's going on here.

00:06:11.000 --> 00:06:17.000
But put yourself in the shoes of someone who has never used R or is just starting to use R.

00:06:17.000 --> 00:06:20.000
An error message like this generates a lot of questions.

00:06:20.000 --> 00:06:23.000
Like, where can I find ggplot2?

00:06:23.000 --> 00:06:26.000
Do I already have ggplot2 installed?

00:06:26.000 --> 00:06:28.000
If not, how do I install it?

00:06:28.000 --> 00:06:30.000
What version am I installing?

00:06:30.000 --> 00:06:33.000
And then where do I put it after I install it?

00:06:33.000 --> 00:06:39.000
That's a lot of questions and can certainly be overwhelming, again, for those that are new to R.

00:06:39.000 --> 00:06:45.000
So to tackle this question and some other related questions, we're going to focus in on these three topics.

00:06:45.000 --> 00:06:51.000
Obviously, we have packages, libraries, and repositories.

00:06:51.000 --> 00:06:56.000
Now, I personally, when I was first learning about package management in R,

00:06:56.000 --> 00:07:01.000
and I was trying to think of some ways to kind of help explain these three concepts,

00:07:01.000 --> 00:07:05.000
I came up with this analogy, which I've used potentially in some other presentations for your group,

00:07:05.000 --> 00:07:08.000
but I always think it's good to go back to.

00:07:08.000 --> 00:07:13.000
So let's say you are in the market for a brand new car.

00:07:13.000 --> 00:07:15.000
So this is you, and you want a new car.

00:07:15.000 --> 00:07:17.000
So what do you do?

00:07:17.000 --> 00:07:20.000
Well, typically, you're going to find yourself at a car dealership.

00:07:20.000 --> 00:07:27.000
So you shop around the car dealership, and eventually you find the car of your dreams, your brand new car.

00:07:27.000 --> 00:07:29.000
So you purchase that car.

00:07:29.000 --> 00:07:31.000
You sit inside of it.

00:07:31.000 --> 00:07:32.000
You turn it on.

00:07:32.000 --> 00:07:37.000
You drive it home, and then you park it in your garage at home.

00:07:37.000 --> 00:07:42.000
Let's say a year goes by, and for some reason, you need another new car.

00:07:42.000 --> 00:07:43.000
So what do you do?

00:07:43.000 --> 00:07:44.000
Same thing.

00:07:44.000 --> 00:07:46.000
You go back to that car dealership.

00:07:46.000 --> 00:07:48.000
You buy another new car.

00:07:48.000 --> 00:07:49.000
You jump inside of it.

00:07:49.000 --> 00:07:50.000
You turn it on.

00:07:50.000 --> 00:07:52.000
You drive it home, and you park it in your garage.

00:07:52.000 --> 00:07:54.000
So now you have two cars in your garage.

00:07:55.000 --> 00:08:02.000
And then you can repeat this process as many times as you want for every new car that you purchase.

00:08:02.000 --> 00:08:10.000
Now, again, a pretty silly analogy, but it does, I think, play nicely with the R ecosystem when it comes to package management.

00:08:10.000 --> 00:08:12.000
So focusing just on the cars.

00:08:12.000 --> 00:08:14.000
Cars are what you interact with.

00:08:14.000 --> 00:08:17.000
You turn them on, and you drive them home.

00:08:17.000 --> 00:08:22.000
These are your packages, because when you're writing code, you interact with packages.

00:08:22.000 --> 00:08:25.000
Now, for your cars, you park them in a garage.

00:08:25.000 --> 00:08:30.000
For your packages, you park them inside of what's known as a library.

00:08:30.000 --> 00:08:33.000
So your garage, in this analogy, is your library.

00:08:33.000 --> 00:08:37.000
And then where do you go shopping for new cars?

00:08:37.000 --> 00:08:39.000
Well, that's your car dealership.

00:08:39.000 --> 00:08:41.000
But where do you go shopping for new packages?

00:08:41.000 --> 00:08:43.000
That's your repository.

00:08:43.000 --> 00:08:50.000
So, again, silly analogy, but personally, it helped me a lot when trying to understand these various concepts.

00:08:52.000 --> 00:08:58.000
Now, again, let's just throw some formal definitions at you, just so you have them.

00:08:58.000 --> 00:09:04.000
In focusing on the R package, a package is a standardized collection of material that extends R.

00:09:04.000 --> 00:09:08.000
So you're going to find code, data, documentation all inside these packages.

00:09:08.000 --> 00:09:11.000
But the take-home message, you interact with packages.

00:09:11.000 --> 00:09:18.000
When you're writing R code, you are typically using functions within packages.

00:09:18.000 --> 00:09:20.000
Next, we have your R library.

00:09:20.000 --> 00:09:29.000
This is a place, and it's going to be a directory, like a physical directory on your computer or server, where R knows to find packages it can use.

00:09:29.000 --> 00:09:33.000
In other words, this is where you store packages.

00:09:33.000 --> 00:09:36.000
And then you have your R repository.

00:09:36.000 --> 00:09:40.000
And this is the primary vehicle for organizing and distributing R packages.

00:09:40.000 --> 00:09:45.000
In other words, this is where you install packages from.

00:09:45.000 --> 00:09:50.000
So we're going to talk about each one of those three, and we're going to start with the package.

00:09:50.000 --> 00:09:52.000
So what is the package?

00:09:52.000 --> 00:09:59.000
I think pretty much probably everyone on the call here has leveraged a package at some point in their R journey here.

00:09:59.000 --> 00:10:02.000
But I think this is a really important statement here.

00:10:02.000 --> 00:10:04.000
It's kind of like outside of today's topic.

00:10:04.000 --> 00:10:09.000
But in R, the fundamental unit of shareable code is the package.

00:10:10.000 --> 00:10:18.000
If you have a piece of R code that you use a lot, and you copy and paste it multiple times, maybe you want to share it with your future self in another project,

00:10:18.000 --> 00:10:25.000
or you want to share it with a colleague, that's where you should take that code, put it inside of a function, place it inside of a package,

00:10:25.000 --> 00:10:28.000
and then you can easily share that package.

00:10:28.000 --> 00:10:31.000
So inside of most packages, you're going to find these four things.

00:10:31.000 --> 00:10:33.000
Obviously, you'll find your code.

00:10:33.000 --> 00:10:39.000
Your package may have some data that's needed for that package, or maybe just some data to play around with.

00:10:39.000 --> 00:10:42.000
All great packages have good documentation.

00:10:42.000 --> 00:10:48.000
And maybe you'll find some unit tests in there as well, just to make sure the package is behaving correctly.

00:10:48.000 --> 00:10:54.000
And all of these get wrapped up into a nice, pretty package, which I purposely put in this hexagon shape,

00:10:54.000 --> 00:11:01.000
because as many of you know, authors of packages love to create what's known as hex logos for their packages.

00:11:01.000 --> 00:11:04.000
And here at Posit, we are no exception to this rule.

00:11:04.000 --> 00:11:12.000
We've created tons of open source packages, and here I'm just showing a handful of them, some of our more popular ones.

00:11:12.000 --> 00:11:16.000
So, for example, we have Shiny for creating interactive web apps using R.

00:11:16.000 --> 00:11:18.000
There's also a Python equivalent as well.

00:11:18.000 --> 00:11:23.000
R Markdown for static reports, GT for tables, a few other packages.

00:11:23.000 --> 00:11:30.000
And then you can see down here, ggplot2, which we've already introduced to your team for data visualization.

00:11:30.000 --> 00:11:36.000
And we're really just going to focus in on ggplot2 today for this workshop.

00:11:36.000 --> 00:11:40.000
So when it comes to packages, there's really two big questions that we need to answer.

00:11:40.000 --> 00:11:43.000
How do you install it, and how do you then load it?

00:11:43.000 --> 00:11:46.000
So looking at the first question, how do you install a package?

00:11:46.000 --> 00:11:51.000
And going back to the car analogy, this is on par of trying to purchase the car.

00:11:51.000 --> 00:11:55.000
So how do you purchase the package, install the package?

00:11:55.000 --> 00:11:59.000
Fortunately, within R, there's a very intuitive function called install.packages.

00:11:59.000 --> 00:12:03.000
And then in open quotes and parentheses, we just give it the name of the package.

00:12:03.000 --> 00:12:07.000
So that will install the package so it becomes yours.

00:12:07.000 --> 00:12:12.000
But once you've purchased said package, you need to be able to turn it on,

00:12:12.000 --> 00:12:15.000
just like you would turn on a car so you can drive it home.

00:12:15.000 --> 00:12:20.000
So to load a package into your environment so you can use all the great functions inside of it,

00:12:20.000 --> 00:12:22.000
we use the library function.

00:12:22.000 --> 00:12:24.000
And same syntax, open parentheses.

00:12:25.000 --> 00:12:29.000
The quotes here are actually optional, but sometimes it's useful just to know that you can use quotes.

00:12:29.000 --> 00:12:32.000
So for both of these functions, you can always have the package name in quotes,

00:12:32.000 --> 00:12:36.000
and you just give it the package name.

00:12:36.000 --> 00:12:38.000
So knowing what you know now about packages,

00:12:38.000 --> 00:12:41.000
let's go back to that error message we saw on the first slide

00:12:41.000 --> 00:12:44.000
where we tried to load the ggplot2 package,

00:12:44.000 --> 00:12:48.000
but we got an error message saying there's no package called ggplot2.

00:12:48.000 --> 00:12:50.000
So what's going on here?

00:12:50.000 --> 00:12:56.000
Well, it turns out we tried to load a package without first installing it.

00:12:56.000 --> 00:13:03.000
This is basically trying to turn on a car without actually owning the car.

00:13:03.000 --> 00:13:06.000
So we're going to jump over to our first live demo.

00:13:06.000 --> 00:13:10.000
And again, if you have RStudio open on your computer

00:13:10.000 --> 00:13:12.000
or if you're logged into pods at Workbench, anywhere,

00:13:12.000 --> 00:13:16.000
feel free to follow along and you can run some of these commands with me.

00:13:17.000 --> 00:13:20.000
But we're going to go ahead and walk through the process of installing

00:13:20.000 --> 00:13:22.000
and loading your very first R package.

00:13:22.000 --> 00:13:27.000
And again, we're going to focus in here on ggplot2.

00:13:27.000 --> 00:13:30.000
Now I'm going to use Posit Workbench for my environment.

00:13:30.000 --> 00:13:34.000
So this is an RStudio session hosted in Posit Workbench.

00:13:34.000 --> 00:13:37.000
And what you're seeing over here in this top left quadrant,

00:13:37.000 --> 00:13:39.000
this is an R Markdown document.

00:13:39.000 --> 00:13:44.000
I have some code here in these code chunks interspersed with some text right here.

00:13:44.000 --> 00:13:46.000
So let me just go ahead and set the stage here.

00:13:46.000 --> 00:13:49.000
And we're going to come down to this first code chunk

00:13:49.000 --> 00:13:53.000
where we're going to try to load the ggplot2 package.

00:13:53.000 --> 00:13:56.000
Now before I run this code chunk, I want you to think of this environment

00:13:56.000 --> 00:13:59.000
like a blank slate, like you just installed R for the first time.

00:13:59.000 --> 00:14:01.000
You just installed RStudio.

00:14:01.000 --> 00:14:03.000
You go to load ggplot2.

00:14:03.000 --> 00:14:08.000
So if I run this code, we get that same error message we just saw.

00:14:08.000 --> 00:14:10.000
There is no package called ggplot2.

00:14:10.000 --> 00:14:11.000
But now we know what to do.

00:14:11.000 --> 00:14:12.000
We need to install it.

00:14:12.000 --> 00:14:15.000
We need to purchase said package.

00:14:15.000 --> 00:14:18.000
So we'll come down here to the second.

00:14:18.000 --> 00:14:25.000
Actually, let me go ahead and I'm just going to clear all my output here.

00:14:25.000 --> 00:14:29.000
All right, so we're going to go ahead and install ggplot2.

00:14:29.000 --> 00:14:31.000
So I'm going to go ahead and hit play.

00:14:31.000 --> 00:14:35.000
And again, feel free to run this command in your own environment.

00:14:35.000 --> 00:14:38.000
When you run this, you may see some output that's different from mine.

00:14:38.000 --> 00:14:40.000
And that's totally okay.

00:14:40.000 --> 00:14:42.000
As long as you're not seeing an error message,

00:14:42.000 --> 00:14:46.000
then you can be pretty confident that this package was installed correctly.

00:14:46.000 --> 00:14:48.000
But there's actually some other ways you can check

00:14:48.000 --> 00:14:50.000
to make sure it was installed correctly.

00:14:50.000 --> 00:14:53.000
And one of the easiest ways is just to see what version you installed.

00:14:53.000 --> 00:14:57.000
So there's another function you all can take note of called package version.

00:14:57.000 --> 00:14:59.000
You just feed it the name of the package.

00:14:59.000 --> 00:15:00.000
We can hit play.

00:15:00.000 --> 00:15:04.000
And you can see I have installed 3.4.4.

00:15:04.000 --> 00:15:08.000
That's the version of ggplot2 I just installed.

00:15:08.000 --> 00:15:11.000
So now that I've purchased the package, it is mine,

00:15:11.000 --> 00:15:15.000
I can now turn it on so I can start using some of the functions inside of it.

00:15:15.000 --> 00:15:17.000
And so that's going to be the role of the library function.

00:15:17.000 --> 00:15:19.000
I'll hit play.

00:15:19.000 --> 00:15:20.000
You might see some output.

00:15:20.000 --> 00:15:21.000
You may not see some output.

00:15:21.000 --> 00:15:23.000
Again, as long as you're not seeing an error message,

00:15:23.000 --> 00:15:27.000
then you can be pretty confident that the ggplot2 package is turned on

00:15:27.000 --> 00:15:29.000
and ready to rock.

00:15:29.000 --> 00:15:31.000
That's kind of a side note.

00:15:31.000 --> 00:15:34.000
If you're ever curious to know what packages are kind of loaded

00:15:34.000 --> 00:15:35.000
in your environment and turned on,

00:15:35.000 --> 00:15:38.000
there's the packages tab over here in the bottom right-hand corner,

00:15:38.000 --> 00:15:42.000
and I can search for ggplot2.

00:15:42.000 --> 00:15:45.000
And it's actually not shown here.

00:15:45.000 --> 00:15:46.000
Okay.

00:15:46.000 --> 00:15:47.000
I actually know what's going on.

00:15:47.000 --> 00:15:48.000
We'll just kind of ignore that for right now.

00:15:48.000 --> 00:15:51.000
But you can also load packages by clicking this little button right here.

00:15:51.000 --> 00:15:55.000
But I think my lock file is a little bit different from my active version,

00:15:55.000 --> 00:15:58.000
but we're going to talk about that a little bit later.

00:15:58.000 --> 00:15:59.000
All right.

00:15:59.000 --> 00:16:01.000
So coming back here to this code chunk,

00:16:01.000 --> 00:16:04.000
now that I have ggplot2 turned on and ready to rock,

00:16:04.000 --> 00:16:07.000
I can start using some of the functions inside of it.

00:16:07.000 --> 00:16:11.000
So here we're going to use the ggplot function to create a plot.

00:16:11.000 --> 00:16:14.000
We're going to use the mtcars dataset,

00:16:14.000 --> 00:16:18.000
and we're going to plot on the x-axis, mpg, on the y-axis, wt,

00:16:18.000 --> 00:16:21.000
and we're going to create a scatter plot or a point plot.

00:16:21.000 --> 00:16:23.000
So I'll go ahead and hit play.

00:16:23.000 --> 00:16:26.000
And then here's our beautiful ggplot2, again,

00:16:26.000 --> 00:16:29.000
using the ggplot2 package that we just installed.

00:16:32.000 --> 00:16:35.000
But we still have some lingering questions here.

00:16:35.000 --> 00:16:38.000
Where did I install ggplot2 from?

00:16:38.000 --> 00:16:42.000
So what was my repository or car dealership?

00:16:42.000 --> 00:16:46.000
And then once we installed it, we had to put it somewhere on our computer.

00:16:46.000 --> 00:16:47.000
Where did we put it?

00:16:47.000 --> 00:16:49.000
So what's our library?

00:16:49.000 --> 00:16:52.000
Let's go ahead and talk about repositories first.

00:16:52.000 --> 00:16:56.000
So within R, there are plenty of repositories you can choose from,

00:16:56.000 --> 00:16:58.000
and here I'm just listing a few of them.

00:16:58.000 --> 00:17:01.000
Probably the most popular R repository currently out there

00:17:01.000 --> 00:17:03.000
is something known as CRAN.

00:17:03.000 --> 00:17:07.000
CRAN stands for the Comprehensive R Archive Network.

00:17:07.000 --> 00:17:09.000
And how it works is pretty cool.

00:17:09.000 --> 00:17:12.000
So it's actually not like a single server.

00:17:12.000 --> 00:17:16.000
It's actually a series of servers scattered throughout the world.

00:17:16.000 --> 00:17:19.000
And every single one of those servers is completely identical,

00:17:19.000 --> 00:17:22.000
so they all store the exact same information.

00:17:22.000 --> 00:17:25.000
And because of that, they're often referred to as mirrors.

00:17:25.000 --> 00:17:27.000
So you may hear someone say a CRAN mirror.

00:17:27.000 --> 00:17:31.000
As of March of this year, so a couple months ago now,

00:17:31.000 --> 00:17:36.000
there was over 19,000 R packages on CRAN.

00:17:36.000 --> 00:17:41.000
So, again, CRAN, by far, probably the largest repository of R packages.

00:17:41.000 --> 00:17:44.000
But there's other repositories you can choose from.

00:17:44.000 --> 00:17:47.000
So there may be some folks on the line here that have leveraged packages

00:17:47.000 --> 00:17:49.000
within Bioconductor before.

00:17:49.000 --> 00:17:51.000
So if you're doing any type of bioinformatics,

00:17:51.000 --> 00:17:55.000
Bioconductor could be a great repository of packages.

00:17:55.000 --> 00:17:57.000
And as of, again, March of 2023,

00:17:57.000 --> 00:18:00.000
there's a little over 2,000 packages on Bioconductor.

00:18:00.000 --> 00:18:03.000
But anywhere you can go shopping for a package

00:18:03.000 --> 00:18:06.000
can serve as a source of package, a repository.

00:18:06.000 --> 00:18:09.000
So that can be RForge, it can be GitHub or GitLab,

00:18:09.000 --> 00:18:12.000
anywhere you can install a package from.

00:18:12.000 --> 00:18:16.000
So that begs the question, well, what repository am I using?

00:18:16.000 --> 00:18:18.000
So in your RStudio environment, R environment,

00:18:18.000 --> 00:18:22.000
when you install ggplot2, where did you go shopping?

00:18:22.000 --> 00:18:24.000
You can check that by running this function.

00:18:24.000 --> 00:18:27.000
So the options function, open and close parentheses,

00:18:27.000 --> 00:18:31.000
and in quotes, repos, which is just shorthand for repositories.

00:18:31.000 --> 00:18:35.000
And that will print to the console whatever repository you use

00:18:35.000 --> 00:18:37.000
to install that package from.

00:18:37.000 --> 00:18:40.000
So here in this screenshot, you can see I'm actually pointing

00:18:40.000 --> 00:18:44.000
to an instance of Posit's own CRAN mirror.

00:18:44.000 --> 00:18:47.000
Yours may be this, it may be something different.

00:18:47.000 --> 00:18:50.000
That's totally fine, but this is how you can check.

00:18:50.000 --> 00:18:54.000
It's also worth noting that you can see what repository

00:18:54.000 --> 00:18:57.000
you're using and also change your repository

00:18:57.000 --> 00:18:59.000
using the RStudio IDE.

00:18:59.000 --> 00:19:01.000
If you go to tools, global options, and packages.

00:19:01.000 --> 00:19:04.000
And I'll go ahead and show you this here in a second.

00:19:04.000 --> 00:19:07.000
So let's go back to RStudio and just ask what question,

00:19:07.000 --> 00:19:11.000
what repositories you're using for your environment.

00:19:11.000 --> 00:19:13.000
So again, feel free to run some of these commands

00:19:13.000 --> 00:19:15.000
in your own environment.

00:19:15.000 --> 00:19:17.000
But all I'm going to do right here is I'm going to run

00:19:17.000 --> 00:19:19.000
options repos.

00:19:19.000 --> 00:19:21.000
And that's just going to print to the console right underneath

00:19:21.000 --> 00:19:24.000
this code chunk, my repository.

00:19:24.000 --> 00:19:27.000
It's worth noting that for the most part repositories

00:19:27.000 --> 00:19:30.000
are just going to be URLs, websites.

00:19:30.000 --> 00:19:33.000
So here you can see this website right here.

00:19:33.000 --> 00:19:35.000
Let me quickly talk about this, but we're going to focus in

00:19:35.000 --> 00:19:37.000
on it a little bit later.

00:19:37.000 --> 00:19:42.000
So in the first part of this URL, you see colorado.rstudio.com.

00:19:42.000 --> 00:19:44.000
This is our demo environment here at Posit.

00:19:44.000 --> 00:19:45.000
We call it Colorado.

00:19:45.000 --> 00:19:46.000
I have no idea why.

00:19:46.000 --> 00:19:47.000
We just do.

00:19:47.000 --> 00:19:49.000
And then we can follow the path here.

00:19:49.000 --> 00:19:51.000
We see RSPM.

00:19:51.000 --> 00:19:55.000
RS is RStudio Package Manager or Posit Package Manager.

00:19:55.000 --> 00:19:57.000
We see all Linux jammies.

00:19:57.000 --> 00:19:59.000
So we're pulling in Linux binaries.

00:19:59.000 --> 00:20:00.000
We'll talk about that a little bit later.

00:20:00.000 --> 00:20:03.000
And then I'm pulling in the latest and greatest packages.

00:20:03.000 --> 00:20:06.000
So it's just worth noting that in my environment right here

00:20:06.000 --> 00:20:09.000
in Posit Workbench, I'm pointing to an instance

00:20:09.000 --> 00:20:11.000
of Posit Package Manager.

00:20:11.000 --> 00:20:14.000
But if you run this function in your environment,

00:20:14.000 --> 00:20:15.000
it's likely going to be a bit different.

00:20:15.000 --> 00:20:17.000
But this is how you can check to see

00:20:17.000 --> 00:20:19.000
which repositories you're using.

00:20:22.000 --> 00:20:23.000
Okay, so we talked about packages.

00:20:23.000 --> 00:20:25.000
We talked about repositories.

00:20:25.000 --> 00:20:28.000
Now we're going to focus in on libraries.

00:20:28.000 --> 00:20:32.000
And of the three, libraries tends to be the most complex.

00:20:32.000 --> 00:20:35.000
So we're going to spend a lot of time talking about libraries.

00:20:35.000 --> 00:20:37.000
But before we really dig into it,

00:20:37.000 --> 00:20:38.000
let's just ask the question,

00:20:38.000 --> 00:20:41.000
where did we put ggplot2 once we installed it?

00:20:41.000 --> 00:20:44.000
What is our library?

00:20:44.000 --> 00:20:47.000
So there's another function within R

00:20:47.000 --> 00:20:50.000
that's kind of built into R called .libpats.

00:20:50.000 --> 00:20:52.000
And that will print to your console

00:20:52.000 --> 00:20:56.000
what libraries are currently active in your environment.

00:20:56.000 --> 00:20:58.000
So go ahead and run this in your own environment.

00:20:58.000 --> 00:21:00.000
And it's worth noting that what you're seeing on the screen,

00:21:00.000 --> 00:21:03.000
this is my library, at least in the screenshot.

00:21:03.000 --> 00:21:06.000
Yours 100% is going to be different from mine.

00:21:07.000 --> 00:21:09.000
Because again, this is going to be a directory,

00:21:09.000 --> 00:21:11.000
like a folder on your computer,

00:21:11.000 --> 00:21:13.000
which is unique to your environment.

00:21:13.000 --> 00:21:15.000
So yours is going to be different.

00:21:15.000 --> 00:21:16.000
Let's go ahead and just check it.

00:21:16.000 --> 00:21:19.000
What libraries are you using?

00:21:19.000 --> 00:21:20.000
I'm going to come back here,

00:21:20.000 --> 00:21:23.000
and we're just going to run .libpats.

00:21:23.000 --> 00:21:25.000
No arguments, just the function.

00:21:25.000 --> 00:21:27.000
We'll hit play.

00:21:27.000 --> 00:21:29.000
And you can see here, I actually have two libraries.

00:21:29.000 --> 00:21:31.000
So if you are using something known as Rn,

00:21:31.000 --> 00:21:33.000
you may see multiple libraries.

00:21:33.000 --> 00:21:35.000
But it's going to use this top one by default.

00:21:35.000 --> 00:21:37.000
And so when I go to install a package,

00:21:37.000 --> 00:21:41.000
this is the path on my system where it's going to be placed.

00:21:41.000 --> 00:21:43.000
And I can follow this path if I want to.

00:21:43.000 --> 00:21:46.000
So using my file directory here in the bottom right-hand corner,

00:21:46.000 --> 00:21:49.000
you can see I'm currently within this package management R,

00:21:49.000 --> 00:21:51.000
which is right here.

00:21:51.000 --> 00:21:52.000
So we can just follow the path.

00:21:52.000 --> 00:21:58.000
So I can go to Rn, library 4.2, that guy.

00:21:58.000 --> 00:22:01.000
And here's all the packages that I currently installed on my system.

00:22:01.000 --> 00:22:09.000
And you can see they're actually just directories within this folder.

00:22:09.000 --> 00:22:11.000
All right, some notes about R libraries.

00:22:11.000 --> 00:22:13.000
Some of these points we've already touched upon.

00:22:13.000 --> 00:22:16.000
The first one, R packages, again, are installed into libraries.

00:22:16.000 --> 00:22:19.000
These are directories on your system,

00:22:19.000 --> 00:22:22.000
and they contain a subdirectory for each package installed there,

00:22:22.000 --> 00:22:24.000
as you just saw.

00:22:24.000 --> 00:22:26.000
The second point here is something I have not mentioned yet,

00:22:26.000 --> 00:22:28.000
but I think is really important.

00:22:28.000 --> 00:22:34.000
Libraries, they're going to be associated with a specific version of R.

00:22:34.000 --> 00:22:37.000
So take a look at the path you see here on the bottom of your screen,

00:22:37.000 --> 00:22:41.000
and you'll notice at the very end you see 4.1.

00:22:41.000 --> 00:22:45.000
This library is associated with R version 4.1.

00:22:45.000 --> 00:22:50.000
If I was to install R version 4.2, so another major version of R,

00:22:50.000 --> 00:22:55.000
that's going to create a new library for those packages.

00:22:55.000 --> 00:22:59.000
And then this last point here, library environments are different

00:22:59.000 --> 00:23:02.000
if you're using RStudio on your local machine,

00:23:02.000 --> 00:23:04.000
so on your laptop, for example,

00:23:04.000 --> 00:23:08.000
versus a Posit Workbench or a server-based environment.

00:23:08.000 --> 00:23:11.000
So let's actually talk about that last point here.

00:23:11.000 --> 00:23:15.000
And first, let's go through a scenario where you're running R in RStudio

00:23:15.000 --> 00:23:18.000
on your local machine, let's say your laptop,

00:23:18.000 --> 00:23:21.000
probably many folks here on the call right now.

00:23:21.000 --> 00:23:23.000
So in this environment, it's pretty simple

00:23:23.000 --> 00:23:25.000
because you are the owner of this laptop,

00:23:25.000 --> 00:23:29.000
so there's one user, and there's going to be one R library.

00:23:29.000 --> 00:23:33.000
And this is known as your own personal system library.

00:23:33.000 --> 00:23:36.000
So you can go to your Packages tab, and if you go to the –

00:23:36.000 --> 00:23:41.000
you'll see at the very top, you should see System Library.

00:23:41.000 --> 00:23:43.000
Now, when it comes to a server environment,

00:23:43.000 --> 00:23:47.000
it gets a little bit hairier because now you have a single environment,

00:23:47.000 --> 00:23:52.000
the server, but you have multiple people logging into the server at once.

00:23:52.000 --> 00:23:56.000
And so every single user that does log in,

00:23:56.000 --> 00:23:59.000
they will have their own user library.

00:23:59.000 --> 00:24:02.000
So every single one of these users will have a library

00:24:02.000 --> 00:24:04.000
that's called a user library.

00:24:04.000 --> 00:24:07.000
But there's one additional library which can be really powerful

00:24:07.000 --> 00:24:10.000
and helpful for larger data science teams,

00:24:10.000 --> 00:24:15.000
and that's known as a shared system library.

00:24:15.000 --> 00:24:19.000
So if we take a look at this Packages tab in this environment,

00:24:19.000 --> 00:24:21.000
I'm running here within Posit Workbench,

00:24:21.000 --> 00:24:23.000
you can see all these packages listed here,

00:24:23.000 --> 00:24:25.000
and I actually have two libraries.

00:24:25.000 --> 00:24:27.000
This first one is my user library.

00:24:27.000 --> 00:24:30.000
So, again, these are packages that I've logged into Posit Workbench

00:24:30.000 --> 00:24:32.000
and I've installed.

00:24:32.000 --> 00:24:36.000
So these are my packages, my user packages in my user library.

00:24:36.000 --> 00:24:40.000
But when I logged in for the very first time without doing anything else,

00:24:40.000 --> 00:24:43.000
there were actually some packages already installed for me,

00:24:43.000 --> 00:24:46.000
and that's known as this shared system library.

00:24:46.000 --> 00:24:49.000
So this is something our system administrators set up.

00:24:49.000 --> 00:24:51.000
They installed packages onto the server

00:24:51.000 --> 00:24:54.000
and made them available to everyone.

00:24:54.000 --> 00:24:57.000
So, again, this is good if you have larger data science teams,

00:24:57.000 --> 00:24:59.000
and that way you don't have to install the same package

00:24:59.000 --> 00:25:01.000
for every single user.

00:25:01.000 --> 00:25:06.000
You can just share a package across users.

00:25:06.000 --> 00:25:08.000
All right, but there's one more library I want to talk about

00:25:08.000 --> 00:25:10.000
that wasn't confusing enough.

00:25:10.000 --> 00:25:14.000
And to introduce this library, let's go through a scenario.

00:25:14.000 --> 00:25:17.000
Let's say you have – we'll start right here at Project 1.

00:25:17.000 --> 00:25:19.000
You come in Monday morning.

00:25:19.000 --> 00:25:21.000
Your boss sends you an email with a data set,

00:25:21.000 --> 00:25:23.000
and they want you to analyze it.

00:25:23.000 --> 00:25:25.000
And so you decide you're going to create some plots,

00:25:25.000 --> 00:25:29.000
so you're going to use ggplot2, and we'll just say version 1.

00:25:29.000 --> 00:25:32.000
You create the document or whatever.

00:25:32.000 --> 00:25:34.000
They're really beautiful visualizations,

00:25:34.000 --> 00:25:37.000
and then you send it off for review somewhere.

00:25:37.000 --> 00:25:41.000
Some time goes by, and you get a second project thrown at you,

00:25:41.000 --> 00:25:44.000
and you decide to do the same thing, create some visualizations.

00:25:44.000 --> 00:25:46.000
But there's now a new version of ggplot2.

00:25:46.000 --> 00:25:48.000
We'll just call it version 2.

00:25:48.000 --> 00:25:50.000
So you install the new version.

00:25:50.000 --> 00:25:52.000
Things are going great.

00:25:52.000 --> 00:25:54.000
But let's say while you're working on Project 2,

00:25:54.000 --> 00:25:57.000
Project 1 actually kind of comes back to you.

00:25:57.000 --> 00:25:58.000
So you get an email saying,

00:25:58.000 --> 00:26:00.000
oh, we need you to go back to Project 1

00:26:00.000 --> 00:26:02.000
and redo some of the plots.

00:26:02.000 --> 00:26:05.000
And now you're in a bit of a pickle because Project 1,

00:26:05.000 --> 00:26:09.000
as you remember, it used version 1 of ggplot2.

00:26:09.000 --> 00:26:11.000
So what do you do?

00:26:11.000 --> 00:26:15.000
Well, you could try to kind of revert ggplot2 back to version 1,

00:26:15.000 --> 00:26:17.000
which is probably easier said than done.

00:26:17.000 --> 00:26:21.000
Or you can try to bring ggplot2 up to speed

00:26:21.000 --> 00:26:23.000
with the latest and greatest version,

00:26:23.000 --> 00:26:25.000
which might work or might break some things.

00:26:25.000 --> 00:26:28.000
So it's not great for reproducibility.

00:26:28.000 --> 00:26:32.000
So what would be much nicer is if we could just isolate these two projects

00:26:32.000 --> 00:26:35.000
so that Project 1 always used version 1

00:26:35.000 --> 00:26:38.000
and Project 2 always used version 2.

00:26:38.000 --> 00:26:42.000
And you can do that with the help of something known as RStudio Projects

00:26:42.000 --> 00:26:46.000
in combination with a tool known as renv.

00:26:46.000 --> 00:26:50.000
So renv is another open source R package that we've developed here at Posit.

00:26:50.000 --> 00:26:53.000
And it gives you access to a third library

00:26:53.000 --> 00:26:58.000
or fourth library at this point called a project library.

00:26:58.000 --> 00:27:01.000
So a little bit about RStudio Projects and renv.

00:27:01.000 --> 00:27:03.000
What are they?

00:27:03.000 --> 00:27:06.000
So when you use an RStudio Project,

00:27:06.000 --> 00:27:09.000
that gives this project, whatever you're working on,

00:27:09.000 --> 00:27:11.000
its own working directory.

00:27:11.000 --> 00:27:15.000
And inside of that working directory will be your code, data, results,

00:27:15.000 --> 00:27:18.000
tables, figures, everything associated with that project,

00:27:18.000 --> 00:27:23.000
including the packages needed for this project and only this project.

00:27:23.000 --> 00:27:26.000
And that's through the power of renv.

00:27:26.000 --> 00:27:29.000
So it makes every single project its own isolated environment,

00:27:29.000 --> 00:27:31.000
which makes it projects much easier to share,

00:27:31.000 --> 00:27:34.000
makes your projects much more reproducible.

00:27:34.000 --> 00:27:37.000
And it also gives you access to something known as an renv log file,

00:27:37.000 --> 00:27:40.000
which we'll briefly talk about here in a second.

00:27:40.000 --> 00:27:42.000
But if you've never used projects before,

00:27:42.000 --> 00:27:46.000
let me just quickly introduce you to how to create them.

00:27:46.000 --> 00:27:49.000
There's actually a few different ways you can do it in the RStudio IDE.

00:27:49.000 --> 00:27:51.000
I'm just going to show you one method.

00:27:51.000 --> 00:27:55.000
So if you have an RStudio session open, you can go to File, New Project.

00:27:55.000 --> 00:27:59.000
And that'll bring open this menu here where you can give your project a name.

00:27:59.000 --> 00:28:01.000
And this is going to create a new directory on your computer.

00:28:01.000 --> 00:28:03.000
So give that directory a name,

00:28:03.000 --> 00:28:06.000
where you want to place that directory on your system.

00:28:06.000 --> 00:28:11.000
And then importantly, you want to check this box to use renv with this project,

00:28:11.000 --> 00:28:14.000
because then that's going to give you access to that project library.

00:28:14.000 --> 00:28:16.000
You hit Create Project.

00:28:16.000 --> 00:28:19.000
It's going to open you up in a new RStudio session.

00:28:19.000 --> 00:28:23.000
You should see the name of the project here in the top right corner.

00:28:23.000 --> 00:28:25.000
And then if you click on the Packages tab,

00:28:25.000 --> 00:28:28.000
you should now have access to a project library.

00:28:28.000 --> 00:28:33.000
So again, this library is specific to this project and only this project.

00:28:33.000 --> 00:28:36.000
And then within the file directory, you'll see a few additional files.

00:28:36.000 --> 00:28:41.000
So you'll always see this rproj file within the home directory of your project.

00:28:41.000 --> 00:28:46.000
And then we have this rm directory and we have this rm lock file.

00:28:46.000 --> 00:28:49.000
So I believe we talked about lock files with your team before.

00:28:49.000 --> 00:28:51.000
But just quickly introduce you to lock files.

00:28:51.000 --> 00:28:53.000
This is the first time you're seeing them.

00:28:53.000 --> 00:28:55.000
This is an example lock file.

00:28:55.000 --> 00:28:58.000
And they're very ugly to look at because they're written in JSON format,

00:28:58.000 --> 00:29:00.000
but they're actually pretty easy to read.

00:29:00.000 --> 00:29:02.000
You can start right up here at the very top

00:29:02.000 --> 00:29:06.000
and see what R version was used for this project, so 4.1.

00:29:06.000 --> 00:29:09.000
What active repositories were used for the project.

00:29:09.000 --> 00:29:11.000
So where did this user go and get their packages?

00:29:11.000 --> 00:29:13.000
You can see it's CRAN.

00:29:13.000 --> 00:29:17.000
And then everything else is just information about the packages in this project.

00:29:17.000 --> 00:29:20.000
So here we have two listed, Markdown and MIME.

00:29:20.000 --> 00:29:22.000
You can see their associated versions.

00:29:22.000 --> 00:29:24.000
So that's something that Rnv is really good at,

00:29:24.000 --> 00:29:27.000
is keeping track of what versions of packages you use,

00:29:27.000 --> 00:29:29.000
where you obtain them.

00:29:29.000 --> 00:29:30.000
You can also see this hash here.

00:29:30.000 --> 00:29:32.000
We're not going to talk too much about that today,

00:29:32.000 --> 00:29:36.000
but that's important for global package caching.

00:29:36.000 --> 00:29:40.000
Okay, so to summarize what we talked about with libraries,

00:29:40.000 --> 00:29:43.000
because, again, libraries is a bit confusing.

00:29:43.000 --> 00:29:46.000
Hopefully this flow diagram helps out a little bit.

00:29:46.000 --> 00:29:50.000
But if you just ask the question, if you install a package, where does it go?

00:29:50.000 --> 00:29:54.000
So if you start up here at the very top, we install ggplot2.

00:29:54.000 --> 00:29:58.000
The first question you should ask is, are you using an RStudio project?

00:29:58.000 --> 00:30:01.000
If yes, are you using Rnv?

00:30:01.000 --> 00:30:08.000
And if yes, then the answer is that package is going to go into your project library.

00:30:08.000 --> 00:30:13.000
But if you're not using Rnv, or if you're not within an RStudio project,

00:30:13.000 --> 00:30:16.000
the next question becomes, where are you running R?

00:30:16.000 --> 00:30:19.000
Are you running it on your local desktop or laptop?

00:30:19.000 --> 00:30:23.000
In that case, it'll go into your personal system library.

00:30:23.000 --> 00:30:25.000
Or are you running on a server, like Posit Workbench,

00:30:25.000 --> 00:30:28.000
in which case it'll go into your personal user library.

00:30:28.000 --> 00:30:31.000
So those are kind of like the three main libraries to keep track of

00:30:31.000 --> 00:30:33.000
as you're working through R.

00:30:37.000 --> 00:30:40.000
Okay, so now that we've covered packages, libraries, and repositories,

00:30:40.000 --> 00:30:43.000
let's talk about the not-so-fun stuff.

00:30:43.000 --> 00:30:46.000
And that is package dependency conflicts,

00:30:46.000 --> 00:30:49.000
or basically what happens when things go wrong.

00:30:49.000 --> 00:30:52.000
So let me run through a scenario with you.

00:30:52.000 --> 00:30:55.000
I'm going to pick a random date. This is completely arbitrary.

00:30:55.000 --> 00:30:58.000
We'll say January 1, 2020.

00:30:58.000 --> 00:31:01.000
You open up R and RStudio, and you install a package.

00:31:01.000 --> 00:31:05.000
We'll focus on the tbl package, which some of you may be familiar with.

00:31:05.000 --> 00:31:09.000
So we go and install .packages, the tbl package.

00:31:09.000 --> 00:31:12.000
It is very common in R, and also in Python,

00:31:12.000 --> 00:31:16.000
for packages to depend on other packages.

00:31:16.000 --> 00:31:19.000
So by installing the tbl package, it actually, by default,

00:31:20.000 --> 00:31:23.000
will install three dependencies, the rlang, cli, and cran packages.

00:31:26.000 --> 00:31:29.000
Now, again, on this date, we installed tbl and all those dependencies,

00:31:29.000 --> 00:31:32.000
so they're all being installed at the exact same time.

00:31:32.000 --> 00:31:35.000
And there's actually a cool thing that cran does.

00:31:35.000 --> 00:31:38.000
So again, that big repository of R packages.

00:31:38.000 --> 00:31:41.000
Cran always tests to ensure that the latest packages

00:31:41.000 --> 00:31:44.000
always work together.

00:31:44.000 --> 00:31:47.000
So if you install these packages on the exact same date,

00:31:48.000 --> 00:31:51.000
all the packages and the versions and dependencies,

00:31:51.000 --> 00:31:54.000
they should all work nicely together. You shouldn't get any conflicts.

00:31:54.000 --> 00:31:57.000
But let's fast forward a month.

00:31:57.000 --> 00:32:00.000
I'm just taking some arbitrary time.

00:32:00.000 --> 00:32:03.000
And you go back into that same R environment where you install tbl.

00:32:03.000 --> 00:32:06.000
And you now install another package,

00:32:06.000 --> 00:32:09.000
and we'll focus on the packagedown package.

00:32:09.000 --> 00:32:12.000
So you install packagedown. It turns out packagedown

00:32:12.000 --> 00:32:15.000
actually has the same three dependencies,

00:32:15.000 --> 00:32:18.000
rlang, cli, and cran.

00:32:18.000 --> 00:32:21.000
But because this is being installed a month later,

00:32:21.000 --> 00:32:24.000
it turns out there's actually some new versions of these various dependencies,

00:32:24.000 --> 00:32:27.000
which is why they're kind of shaded in this darker gray color.

00:32:27.000 --> 00:32:30.000
So by installing packagedown on February 1st,

00:32:30.000 --> 00:32:33.000
it'll automatically update the rlang, cli, and cran packages.

00:32:33.000 --> 00:32:36.000
But what it will not do is update the tbl package itself.

00:32:36.000 --> 00:32:39.000
And now you're in a bit of a broken state

00:32:39.000 --> 00:32:42.000
because you have an old version of tbl

00:32:42.000 --> 00:32:45.000
that's trying to use new versions of its dependencies,

00:32:45.000 --> 00:32:48.000
and you may run into some issues where functions aren't behaving as expected.

00:32:48.000 --> 00:32:51.000
So how do we get around this?

00:32:51.000 --> 00:32:54.000
Well, I mentioned before that cran tests to ensure

00:32:54.000 --> 00:32:57.000
that the latest packages always work together.

00:32:57.000 --> 00:33:00.000
So because of that, it's very common for data science teams

00:33:00.000 --> 00:33:03.000
to do something what's known as freezing a repository

00:33:03.000 --> 00:33:06.000
to a set date.

00:33:06.000 --> 00:33:09.000
So let me explain how this works.

00:33:09.000 --> 00:33:12.000
So again, we have two dates right here, and we have January 1st, 2020.

00:33:12.000 --> 00:33:15.000
And let's say that you as the user or your administrator

00:33:15.000 --> 00:33:18.000
decides to freeze your repository

00:33:18.000 --> 00:33:21.000
to this date, February 1st.

00:33:21.000 --> 00:33:24.000
You install tbl, things go great, and then you fast forward

00:33:24.000 --> 00:33:27.000
to February 1st. But even though it's February 1st,

00:33:27.000 --> 00:33:30.000
your repository is still frozen to January 1st.

00:33:30.000 --> 00:33:33.000
So you go to install packagedown in February,

00:33:33.000 --> 00:33:36.000
but it still installs it as if it's January 1st.

00:33:36.000 --> 00:33:39.000
So no matter when you installed any subsequent packages,

00:33:39.000 --> 00:33:42.000
they're all being installed as if it's the same time.

00:33:42.000 --> 00:33:45.000
So all these packages, again, should work together

00:33:45.000 --> 00:33:48.000
because that's the added service that CRAN provides.

00:33:48.000 --> 00:33:51.000
Okay, now that we've talked about a bunch of different things,

00:33:51.000 --> 00:33:54.000
you might have some questions kind of circulating in your head

00:33:54.000 --> 00:33:57.000
as you start to devise your own package management strategy.

00:33:57.000 --> 00:34:00.000
You know, things like who is going to be responsible

00:34:00.000 --> 00:34:03.000
for reproducing the environment?

00:34:03.000 --> 00:34:06.000
Is that going to be up to the data scientists, the users,

00:34:06.000 --> 00:34:09.000
or is it going to be up to my system administrators?

00:34:09.000 --> 00:34:12.000
Also, how open is the environment? Can a user

00:34:12.000 --> 00:34:15.000
install a new package, or are they going to be locked down to a specific

00:34:15.000 --> 00:34:18.000
version? Should we be using these shared

00:34:18.000 --> 00:34:21.000
system libraries or just specific user libraries?

00:34:21.000 --> 00:34:24.000
And really, you have to weigh the pros and cons

00:34:24.000 --> 00:34:27.000
specific to your team. It's nice to talk to

00:34:27.000 --> 00:34:30.000
other teams as well and to kind of see what they're doing, but ultimately

00:34:30.000 --> 00:34:33.000
it's just to find a solution that kind of meets your team's

00:34:33.000 --> 00:34:36.000
needs. Now having said

00:34:36.000 --> 00:34:39.000
that, we have worked with a bunch of teams here at Posit

00:34:39.000 --> 00:34:42.000
where we've seen package management strategies succeed

00:34:42.000 --> 00:34:45.000
and we've seen some strategies not so succeed.

00:34:45.000 --> 00:34:48.000
And so what you're seeing on this plot right here,

00:34:48.000 --> 00:34:51.000
we're showing you a few different strategies that we're going to

00:34:51.000 --> 00:34:54.000
touch upon. On the y-axis, we're looking at package

00:34:54.000 --> 00:34:57.000
access. So that's asking, can a user

00:34:57.000 --> 00:35:00.000
install whatever package they want? So is it open,

00:35:00.000 --> 00:35:03.000
or is it fairly locked down? So they're kind of constrained to specific

00:35:03.000 --> 00:35:06.000
packages or specific versions. And then

00:35:06.000 --> 00:35:09.000
on the x-axis, we're looking at who is responsible for

00:35:09.000 --> 00:35:12.000
reproducing the environment. Is that going to be up to your system

00:35:12.000 --> 00:35:15.000
administrators, or is it going to be up to the data scientists?

00:35:15.000 --> 00:35:18.000
We find teams have the most success

00:35:18.000 --> 00:35:21.000
somewhere along this diagonal. And we're

00:35:21.000 --> 00:35:24.000
actually going to talk about these three strategies. We're going to start with snapshot,

00:35:24.000 --> 00:35:27.000
then we'll talk about shared baseline, and then finally a validated

00:35:27.000 --> 00:35:30.000
strategy. And then we'll just briefly touch

00:35:30.000 --> 00:35:33.000
upon some of these other strategies where we see things go a little

00:35:33.000 --> 00:35:36.000
bit haywire. So let's go ahead and start with

00:35:36.000 --> 00:35:39.000
snapshot in the top right corner here. For

00:35:39.000 --> 00:35:42.000
every single one of these strategies, we'll kind of talk about what

00:35:42.000 --> 00:35:45.000
they are and then some pros and cons of each.

00:35:45.000 --> 00:35:48.000
So in a snapshot strategy, users are able

00:35:48.000 --> 00:35:51.000
to freely access and install whatever package

00:35:51.000 --> 00:35:54.000
they want, but you must be using RStudio

00:35:54.000 --> 00:35:57.000
projects and that renv package we talked about before.

00:35:57.000 --> 00:36:00.000
You have to be using that renv lock file.

00:36:00.000 --> 00:36:03.000
So in this scenario, users are going to have the

00:36:03.000 --> 00:36:06.000
full responsibility to record the dependencies

00:36:06.000 --> 00:36:09.000
needed for a project. So in a typical workflow,

00:36:09.000 --> 00:36:12.000
you would create a project, you then write some code,

00:36:12.000 --> 00:36:15.000
install some packages, write more code, install other packages,

00:36:15.000 --> 00:36:18.000
and you use that renv package to

00:36:18.000 --> 00:36:21.000
snapshot your environment, to record what packages you're using.

00:36:21.000 --> 00:36:24.000
That's going to update that lock file, which you can then use

00:36:24.000 --> 00:36:27.000
to restore your environment if needed.

00:36:27.000 --> 00:36:30.000
Now the pros for a snapshot is that it definitely gives

00:36:30.000 --> 00:36:33.000
users access to pretty much any package and any version

00:36:33.000 --> 00:36:36.000
they want to use. And the

00:36:36.000 --> 00:36:39.000
second point right here, I put it as a pro, but depending on your

00:36:39.000 --> 00:36:42.000
team, you may consider it a con. It's really going to

00:36:42.000 --> 00:36:45.000
require little to no IT or sysadmin involvement.

00:36:45.000 --> 00:36:48.000
It's really going to be on the shoulders of the users.

00:36:48.000 --> 00:36:51.000
And that kind of leads me to my major

00:36:51.000 --> 00:36:54.000
con here, is that if you're brand new to R and now

00:36:54.000 --> 00:36:57.000
you're being tasked with keeping track of every package you're

00:36:57.000 --> 00:37:00.000
using and the versions, that can be a slight

00:37:00.000 --> 00:37:03.000
barrier for those that are brand new to R.

00:37:03.000 --> 00:37:06.000
Now it's worth noting that if you

00:37:06.000 --> 00:37:09.000
are running RStudio locally on your personal

00:37:09.000 --> 00:37:12.000
laptop, we'd certainly recommend that you use

00:37:12.000 --> 00:37:15.000
this strategy for all of your projects.

00:37:15.000 --> 00:37:18.000
Okay, the

00:37:18.000 --> 00:37:21.000
second strategy we're going to talk about is something known as a shared

00:37:21.000 --> 00:37:24.000
baseline. And it's just like a side note, this is actually what we use

00:37:24.000 --> 00:37:27.000
internally here at Posit. In this strategy,

00:37:27.000 --> 00:37:30.000
all or most of CRAN, so all 19,

00:37:30.000 --> 00:37:33.000
20,000 packages of CRAN are made available

00:37:33.000 --> 00:37:36.000
to every single user via that shared

00:37:36.000 --> 00:37:39.000
system library. But users are

00:37:39.000 --> 00:37:42.000
still able to freely access and install any

00:37:42.000 --> 00:37:45.000
package they want, any version they want,

00:37:45.000 --> 00:37:48.000
and they can install it into their own project and or user

00:37:48.000 --> 00:37:51.000
library. So the reason why

00:37:51.000 --> 00:37:54.000
we really like this strategy, it's good for both those

00:37:54.000 --> 00:37:57.000
that are new to R and more advanced users.

00:37:57.000 --> 00:38:00.000
For those that are new, all these packages are already there available

00:38:00.000 --> 00:38:03.000
to them. But for the advanced R users, they can still

00:38:03.000 --> 00:38:06.000
reach out and grab a development version of a package

00:38:06.000 --> 00:38:09.000
or the latest and greatest. It can also

00:38:09.000 --> 00:38:12.000
reduce duplicate package installs across users.

00:38:12.000 --> 00:38:15.000
So I mentioned before that when you use that shared

00:38:15.000 --> 00:38:18.000
baseline strategy, that prevents every single user

00:38:18.000 --> 00:38:21.000
installing the same package into their own user library, and especially

00:38:21.000 --> 00:38:24.000
if you have a large data science team, that can be a bit of a waste of space.

00:38:24.000 --> 00:38:27.000
I do put this asterisk here, though, because for the most

00:38:27.000 --> 00:38:30.000
part, packages in R are not very big. They're just a series

00:38:30.000 --> 00:38:33.000
of text files. So it's not really going to take up

00:38:33.000 --> 00:38:36.000
that much space on your system, but it can be a way to save

00:38:36.000 --> 00:38:39.000
up, I know, a couple megabytes.

00:38:39.000 --> 00:38:42.000
Now the cons here, if you're not

00:38:42.000 --> 00:38:45.000
running Posit within a server environment, then this

00:38:45.000 --> 00:38:48.000
strategy is not going to be available to you. So it's not going to be available

00:38:48.000 --> 00:38:51.000
for desktop R users. And then that shared

00:38:51.000 --> 00:38:54.000
library, it may not include the latest and greatest,

00:38:54.000 --> 00:38:57.000
and it's ultimately going to be controlled by your system administrators.

00:38:57.000 --> 00:39:00.000
The last

00:39:00.000 --> 00:39:03.000
strategy we'll talk about is something known as a

00:39:03.000 --> 00:39:06.000
validated strategy. And this is a very popular strategy,

00:39:06.000 --> 00:39:09.000
especially amongst our pharmaceutical, our

00:39:09.000 --> 00:39:12.000
life sciences groups, folks that are going to be

00:39:12.000 --> 00:39:15.000
submitting things to, say, some regulatory

00:39:15.000 --> 00:39:18.000
agency like the FDA here in the States.

00:39:18.000 --> 00:39:21.000
So in a validated strategy, it's going to restrict

00:39:21.000 --> 00:39:24.000
access to a particular set of packages that

00:39:24.000 --> 00:39:27.000
your team deems as validated.

00:39:27.000 --> 00:39:30.000
Now I put validated in quotes because

00:39:30.000 --> 00:39:33.000
a question that I routinely get is, hey, Ryan, is

00:39:33.000 --> 00:39:36.000
this package considered validated or not? I would love

00:39:36.000 --> 00:39:39.000
to be able to answer that question. But unfortunately, every single team

00:39:39.000 --> 00:39:42.000
is unique. And what one team may consider

00:39:42.000 --> 00:39:45.000
something validated, another team may not. And so

00:39:45.000 --> 00:39:48.000
every single team kind of has to create their own series

00:39:48.000 --> 00:39:51.000
of checks to determine if a package

00:39:51.000 --> 00:39:54.000
is considered validated and use their own judgment.

00:39:55.000 --> 00:39:58.000
Now, also for users of a validated

00:39:58.000 --> 00:40:01.000
environment, if they want to use a package that's not currently

00:40:01.000 --> 00:40:04.000
considered validated, then they're kind of out of luck and

00:40:04.000 --> 00:40:07.000
they have to go through an approval process to hopefully get that

00:40:07.000 --> 00:40:10.000
package validated in their environment.

00:40:11.000 --> 00:40:14.000
Now, the pros here with a validated strategy and

00:40:14.000 --> 00:40:17.000
why it's so important for our pharmaceutical groups

00:40:17.000 --> 00:40:20.000
is that you can confidently recreate the same

00:40:20.000 --> 00:40:23.000
environment outcome. So if you go to submit something

00:40:23.000 --> 00:40:26.000
to the FDA, you want to make sure that the results,

00:40:26.000 --> 00:40:29.000
the same thing, you'll get results today, you'll get the same results

00:40:29.000 --> 00:40:32.000
a week from now, a year from now, 10 years from now. So you

00:40:32.000 --> 00:40:35.000
really have to make sure that these analyses do not change at

00:40:35.000 --> 00:40:38.000
all. And you can trust what's in your environment.

00:40:38.000 --> 00:40:41.000
You've done your homework. You know every single thing about every

00:40:41.000 --> 00:40:44.000
single package in your environment. So you can be very confident, be very

00:40:44.000 --> 00:40:47.000
safe in this validated environment. Now, there's

00:40:47.000 --> 00:40:50.000
certainly going to be quite a few cons. It will require

00:40:50.000 --> 00:40:53.000
a lot more IT and sysadmin involvement.

00:40:53.000 --> 00:40:56.000
Also, maintaining a validated environment is not a trivial

00:40:56.000 --> 00:40:59.000
task. And I've worked with groups that have dedicated teams

00:40:59.000 --> 00:41:02.000
just to maintaining a validated environment.

00:41:02.000 --> 00:41:05.000
And then finally, users can be constrained

00:41:05.000 --> 00:41:08.000
to select packages. So if there's

00:41:08.000 --> 00:41:11.000
if they see online or on social media, there's a new package

00:41:11.000 --> 00:41:14.000
with a function that works perfect for them, they may not

00:41:14.000 --> 00:41:17.000
have access to it because it's not considered validated.

00:41:18.000 --> 00:41:21.000
All right, another flow diagram. We're not going to

00:41:21.000 --> 00:41:24.000
talk about this one. But again, when I share the slides,

00:41:24.000 --> 00:41:27.000
you can read through this. And what I'm trying to do is

00:41:27.000 --> 00:41:30.000
guide users into what package management

00:41:30.000 --> 00:41:33.000
strategy they should at least consider. So starting

00:41:33.000 --> 00:41:36.000
here with the user at the very top. So you can see

00:41:36.000 --> 00:41:39.000
in green here, the three strategies we just talked about, snapshot,

00:41:39.000 --> 00:41:42.000
shared baseline and validated. But here

00:41:42.000 --> 00:41:45.000
in red, we also have some strategies which tend not to be

00:41:45.000 --> 00:41:48.000
so good. And their names kind of

00:41:48.000 --> 00:41:51.000
kind of tip the hat to what they are.

00:41:51.000 --> 00:41:54.000
So the first strategy is known as Wild West.

00:41:54.000 --> 00:41:57.000
And so in a Wild West, there's basically

00:41:57.000 --> 00:42:00.000
no regard for reproducibility. They can install whatever

00:42:00.000 --> 00:42:03.000
package they want into whatever library they want, whatever version.

00:42:03.000 --> 00:42:06.000
This is where you run into those package dependency

00:42:06.000 --> 00:42:09.000
conflicts most frequently. We also

00:42:09.000 --> 00:42:12.000
have something known as a ticket system. It's very similar

00:42:12.000 --> 00:42:15.000
to a validated environment because a user will

00:42:15.000 --> 00:42:18.000
require to have to submit a ticket

00:42:18.000 --> 00:42:21.000
in order to get access to a package. But the issue

00:42:21.000 --> 00:42:24.000
is that the folks that are approving said tickets don't

00:42:24.000 --> 00:42:27.000
have much regard for reproducibility. And they can just either deny

00:42:27.000 --> 00:42:30.000
or just add packages willy nilly, which could also

00:42:30.000 --> 00:42:33.000
result in dependency conflicts.

00:42:33.000 --> 00:42:36.000
And then we have a blocked environment, which is just a

00:42:36.000 --> 00:42:39.000
lose-lose situation for both sides of the coin.

00:42:39.000 --> 00:42:42.000
In a blocked environment, usually the Internet is cut off.

00:42:42.000 --> 00:42:45.000
There's no way to reach out externally for packages.

00:42:45.000 --> 00:42:48.000
And so in order to use functions outside

00:42:48.000 --> 00:42:51.000
of base R, users are going to have to figure out

00:42:51.000 --> 00:42:54.000
some backdoor ways to get packages in there and it causes security

00:42:54.000 --> 00:42:57.000
concerns. So this is never a good solution really

00:42:57.000 --> 00:43:00.000
for any team.

00:43:00.000 --> 00:43:03.000
So we're getting pretty close to the end here.

00:43:03.000 --> 00:43:06.000
And we've talked about a lot of different things from the

00:43:06.000 --> 00:43:09.000
perspective of your data scientists, your developers,

00:43:09.000 --> 00:43:12.000
but also your system administrators and your IT teams.

00:43:12.000 --> 00:43:15.000
Things like what repositories are we going

00:43:15.000 --> 00:43:18.000
to use? Are we going to use CRAN, Bioconductor? Are we going to pull

00:43:18.000 --> 00:43:21.000
packages from source? Are we going to use Python

00:43:21.000 --> 00:43:24.000
packages, which we haven't talked about today?

00:43:24.000 --> 00:43:27.000
Where are we going to be running code? Are we going to have users leverage

00:43:27.000 --> 00:43:30.000
their own laptops or are we going to use Posit Workbench, a server-based

00:43:30.000 --> 00:43:33.000
environment? And then for our repositories, are we going to

00:43:33.000 --> 00:43:36.000
make them the latest and greatest packages available? Are we going

00:43:36.000 --> 00:43:39.000
to freeze a repository to a specific date?

00:43:39.000 --> 00:43:42.000
So that's a lot of different questions I have to answer.

00:43:42.000 --> 00:43:45.000
So what we've done here at Posit is create a tool to hopefully

00:43:45.000 --> 00:43:48.000
help simplify this a bit. And that's called

00:43:48.000 --> 00:43:51.000
Posit Package Manager.

00:43:51.000 --> 00:43:54.000
So if you've never heard of Posit Package Manager before,

00:43:54.000 --> 00:43:57.000
here's just a few bullet points that get you up to speed.

00:43:57.000 --> 00:44:00.000
Posit Package Manager, just like all of our

00:44:01.000 --> 00:44:04.000
professional tools, these are internal solutions.

00:44:04.000 --> 00:44:07.000
So they can be installed on a Linux server, either on-prem,

00:44:07.000 --> 00:44:10.000
like literally physically next to you, or they can be

00:44:10.000 --> 00:44:13.000
installed in whatever cloud environment you want.

00:44:13.000 --> 00:44:16.000
But importantly, they can stay within your network, within your

00:44:16.000 --> 00:44:19.000
firewall. So that can be really important for teams that don't

00:44:19.000 --> 00:44:22.000
have any outside access to the Internet.

00:44:22.000 --> 00:44:25.000
And you can do some cool things with it, like you can have your own

00:44:25.000 --> 00:44:28.000
NHS CRAN mirror if you wanted to. So all 19,000

00:44:28.000 --> 00:44:31.000
packages on CRAN, you can have your own personal CRAN mirror.

00:44:31.000 --> 00:44:34.000
Also, for anyone on the line that develops

00:44:34.000 --> 00:44:37.000
their own packages, either in R or Python, you can

00:44:37.000 --> 00:44:40.000
now give those packages a home. So most times

00:44:40.000 --> 00:44:43.000
folks will have them hosted on GitHub or something like that, which

00:44:43.000 --> 00:44:46.000
if they're public, then that's great, but

00:44:46.000 --> 00:44:49.000
maybe if they're not public, or maybe versioning can be an

00:44:49.000 --> 00:44:52.000
issue, you can now host them on Package Manager

00:44:52.000 --> 00:44:55.000
and easily install them and share them across your team.

00:44:55.000 --> 00:44:58.000
And then you can create customized repositories.

00:44:58.000 --> 00:45:01.000
So we only talked about CRAN, but you can create your own subsets

00:45:01.000 --> 00:45:04.000
of repositories and freeze them to specific

00:45:04.000 --> 00:45:07.000
dates, and I'll show you that here in a second.

00:45:07.000 --> 00:45:10.000
But this fourth bullet point is really the main take-home message,

00:45:10.000 --> 00:45:13.000
is that Package Manager is designed to be your

00:45:13.000 --> 00:45:16.000
one-stop shop. If we go back to our

00:45:16.000 --> 00:45:19.000
car dealership analogy, so you remember

00:45:19.000 --> 00:45:22.000
a repository is a car dealership. Let's say there's

00:45:22.000 --> 00:45:25.000
a new dealership that shows up on the street and just buys

00:45:25.000 --> 00:45:28.000
all of the other local dealerships, and now it becomes this one

00:45:28.000 --> 00:45:31.000
mega dealership. That's essentially what Package

00:45:31.000 --> 00:45:34.000
Manager is, is that you don't have to worry about reaching out to

00:45:34.000 --> 00:45:37.000
all these various sources, you can just bring them all together into

00:45:37.000 --> 00:45:40.000
a centralized location. So you can serve CRAN packages,

00:45:40.000 --> 00:45:43.000
Bioconductor, PyPI, all within

00:45:43.000 --> 00:45:46.000
one location. The last two

00:45:46.000 --> 00:45:49.000
points are kind of more aimed to your system administrators.

00:45:49.000 --> 00:45:52.000
You can easily manage package and system dependencies using

